		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message29043813">I realize youtube links are terrible for posterity's sake, but for those here and now: <a href="http://youtu.be/KSwbnUQJGnA" target="_blank" rel="nofollow"><a href="http://youtu.be/KSwbnUQJGnA" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://youtu.be/KSwbnUQJGnA</a></a> (in case you are too lazy to torrent a 6-minute video).<br />
<br />
As with the majority of Shinkai's works, Dareka no Manazashi is beautiful. The colors are sumptuous, the shadows are brilliant and picturesque, the work as a whole feels polished. It's also self-aware of its status as a moving painting by dropping blobs of visuals onto a creamy white canvas. Like Kuiper says, the animation often lingers from one visual to the next. I imagine this is for a sentimentalist intent, and of which serves it purpose well. Shinkai-branded "emotion" seems to work best in shorts like theseâ€”I believe it's not the content that makes this palatable over something like Kotonoha no Niwa's drama, but the length.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: center;"><!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/clubs.php?cid=40791">QD</a><!--center--></div></div></td>
