		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message29052863">'Kay.  Does this mean I have to be that disagreeing voice at the back of the room?<br />
I guess so.<br />
I'm actually not very familiar with Shinkai's works so I can't really compare objectively in that sense.  I can agree that, at the very least, claims of his animation being awesome are not made for no reason.  However, did I miss something somewhere?  Is this not just a commercial for a real estate development?  I dunno, the luster of the work wears off when I know why it exists in the first place.  Please correct me if I'm wrong here.<br />
As far as the story goes, I actually thought it wasn't that strong.  The thing about Shinkai's work that I can determine from what little I've seen is that the art makes the drama and romance linger more than if it was in a different work or a different medium.  Even something you might find corny can be made effective with Shinkai's style of animation.  That's not to say that this story was corny or anything.  I just thought that the drama was bit contrived.  The daughter leaving the house, the father being alone, the elder neglect, the cat dying.  I mean... I dunno.  Maybe I'm just a heartless bastard.  It feels like I've seen it all before, maybe not in anime, but somewhere.<br />
<br />
...I'm probably just a heartless bastard.</div><div style="margin-top: 8px;"><em>Modified by leaveit2me, 03-03-14, 8:56 AM</em></div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig">In God, we trust.  All others pay cash.</div></td>
