		  <td width="135" class="forum_boardrow2" style="border-width: 0px 0px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="messageuser29055211" style="padding-bottom: 2px;"><a href="/profile/Kuiper"><strong>Kuiper</strong></a></div>
		  
		  <a href="/profile/Kuiper"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/useravatars/331692.png" vspace="2" border="0"></a>
		  <br>
		  Offline<br>
		  Joined: May 2010<br>
		  Posts: 74
		  </td>
		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message29055211"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>leaveit2me said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>I dunno, the luster of the work wears off when I know why it exists in the first place.  Please correct me if I'm wrong here.<!--quote--></div><br />
This could be a discussion all on its own, but I feel it's worth pointing out that the vast, vast majority of anime exists for commercial purposes, that is to say, it's created with the intent of making money.  I'd argue that a work like this where the commercial sponsorship is largely separate from the messaging of the work is <em>way</em> less gross than many commercial anime that are engineered for the purpose of selling a larger number of copies to make more money.  (Examples of this include the Madoka movies, the Evangelion remakes, the Monogatari sequels, and to varying extents, most long-running manga series and their adaptations.)<br />
<br />
In short, which would you rather have:<br />
<br />
<div class="quotetext">"Here's a wad of cash.  Make something beautiful that we would be proud to associate with our brand."<!--quote--></div><br />
<br />
or<br />
<br />
<div class="quotetext">"Here's a wad of cash.  Make something that will appeal to otaku superconsumers so that they are compelled to go out and spend hundreds of dollars on blu-rays and merchandise."<!--quote--></div><br />
<br />
Of course that's dichotemizing things a bit unfairly, and it ignores the many cases of anime that exist partly as marketing engines for existing commercial works (e.g. most manga adaptations), but I'd consider it fair to say that the overwhelming majority of anime is made in the pursuit of money.<br />
<br />
Summarizing my thoughts, this feels like a case of Shinkai making a short film because he had a story that he wanted to tell; the source of the funding for the project seems pretty incidental.<br />
<br />
For related reading, I recommend "Make Art Make Money" about Jim Henson (creator of Sesame Street), which discusses the idea of how artists can receive income to fund their creative endeavors without compromising their artistic integrity.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
